bility in science, business, culture, sports or education.\n|If you are over 60 and receive income via pension from overseas.<ref name=\"naver.com\"/>\n|If you invest $2 million. If you invested only $500,000, you need to stay more than 3 years on a D-8 visa. If you invest $500,000 in real estate of [[Jeju Province|Jeju]], [[Incheon Free Economic Zone]], [[Busan]]'s [[Haeundae]], [[Pyeongchang]] or [[Yeosu]], you are given a F-2 residence visa and 5 years later, F-5 permanent residence.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edaily.co.kr/news/news_detail.asp?newsId=01118486612514440&mediaCodeNo=257|title='\uc601\uc8fc\uad8c\uc5d0 \uc2dc\uc138 \ucc28\uc775\uc740 \ub364?'\u2026\ube48\ud2c8 \ub9ce\uc740 \ud22c\uc790 \uc774\ubbfc\uc81c|author=|date=4 January 2016|website=\uc774\ub370\uc77c\ub9ac|accessdate=16 March 2018}}</ref>\n|If you have a Ph.D. in a high-tech field and are employed by a Korean firm, earning 4 times the average [[Gross National Income|GNI]] in Korea. If you only have a bachelor's in a high-tech field or a recognized technical certificate issued in Korea, you need to have stayed for at least 3 years and earn 4 times the average [[Gross National Income|GNI]] in Korea.<ref name=\"naver.com\"/>\n|If you have stayed in Korea for more than 2 years under a F-2 visa and are the spouse of a Korean or foreigner with a F-5 permanent residence visa.\n|If you were born to parents who are stateless or were found abandoned within the territory of South Korea as a child, you will automatically get Korean citizenship.\n|\n|\n|If you meet the requirements for naturalization. See [[South Korean nationality law]].\n|If you previously had Korean nationality or either of your parents or grandparents had Korean nationality in the past, you are immediately eligible for a [[List of South Korean visas|F-4 visa]], a practically permanent residence visa that is renewable every 2 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.immigration.go.kr/HP/IMM80/imm_04/imm_0407/imm_407010.jsp|title=Immigration Bureau|author=|date=|website=www.immigration.go.kr|accessdate=16 March 2018}}</ref> If the Korean government recognizes that you made an important contribution to the nation, you are eligible for F-5 permanent residence.<ref name=\"naver.com\"/>\n|-\n! {{flag|Hong Kong|size=15px}}\n|\n| General Employment Policy (GEP); will receive Right of Abode (ROA) in Hong Kong, after 7 years continuous ordinary residence in Hong Kong.\n| General Points Test (GPT)\n|\n| Capital Investment Entrant Scheme (CIES); you need to invest HK$10 million except on real estate;<ref>[http://www.immd.gov.hk/ehtml/faq_cies.htm FAQ New Amendments to the Rules for Capital Investment Entrant Scheme] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120710145601/http://www.immd.gov.hk/ehtml/faq_cies.htm |date=2012-07-10 }}</ref> will receive Right of Abode (ROA) in Hong Kong, after 7 years continuous ordinary residence in Hong Kong.\n| passing General Points Test (GPT) within Quality Migrant Admission Scheme (QMAS)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.immd.gov.hk/ehtml/QMAS.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-02-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070217141254/http://www.immd.gov.hk/ehtml/QMAS.htm |archivedate=2007-02-17 }}; will receive Right of Abode (ROA) in Hong Kong, after 7 years continuous ordinary residence in Hong Kong.</ref>\n|\n| Person under 21 years of age born in Hong Kong of foreigner with HK Permanent ID Card, will receive Right of Abode (ROA) in Hong Kong, but not Chinese nationality.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gov.hk/en/residents/immigration/idcard/roa/verifyeligible.htm|title=Apply for Right of Abode in Hong Kong|author= Immigration Department|date=|website=www.gov.hk|accessdate=16 March 2018}}</ref>\n|\n|\n| Foreigner who is a Hong Kong Permanent ID Card holder may naturalise as Chinese national with [[HKSAR Passport]], if applicant has settle in Hong Kong or Chinese territory, has near relatives of Chinese nationals, and other legitimate reasons.<