a.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?brws_s=1&file_num=nlc008388.5867&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=mhe12pta2k83e08udtq66ot062|title=Item Display - RPM - Library and Archives Canada|publisher=}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|28\n|-\n|US ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicoutfitters.com/topsongs/1969.htm|title=Top 100 Hits of 1969/Top 100 Songs of 1969|publisher=}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|88\n|-\n|US R&B (''Billboard'')<ref name=\"Top69\">[http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/60s/1969/Billboard%201969-12-27.pdf Top Records on 1969 (Based on Billboard Charts)]\", ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', December 27, 1969, pp. 16\u201317. Accessed December 7, 2016.</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|40\n|-\n|US ''Cash Box''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tropicalglen.com/Archives/60s_files/1969YESP.html|title=Cash Box YE Pop Singles: 1969|publisher=|access-date=December 8, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190125055422/http://tropicalglen.com/Archives/60s_files/1969YESP.html|archive-date=January 25, 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|4\n|-\n|}\n\n===All-time charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! Chart (1958-2018)\n! Position\n|-\n|US ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100-60th-anniversary|title=Billboard Hot 100 60th Anniversary Interactive Chart|work=Billboard|accessdate=10 December 2018}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|84\n|}\n\n===Certifications===\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United Kingdom|type=single|artist=Marvin Gaye|title=I Heard It Through the Grapevine|award=Gold|relyear=2004|certyear=2019|accessdate=August 2, 2019}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom|nosales=true|noshipments=true|streaming=true}}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n;Bibliography\n* John Covach, Mark Spicer, ''Sounding Out Pop: Analytical Essays in Popular Music'',  2010, University of Michigan Press\n* Bill Dahl, ''Motown: The Golden Years'', 2011, Krause Publications\n* David N. Howard, ''Sonic Alchemy: Visionary Music Producers and Their Maverick Recordings'', 2004, Hal Leonard Corporation\n* Gerald Posner, ''Motown : Music, Money, Sex, and Power'', 2002, New York: Random House, {{ISBN|0-8129-7468-9}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|marvin-gaye|i-heard-it-through-the-grapevine}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{The Miracles}}\n{{The Miracles singles}}\n{{Marvin Gaye}}\n{{Marvin Gaye singles}}\n{{Gladys Knight & the Pips}}\n{{Creedence}}\n{{The California Raisins}}\n{{Michael McDonald}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:I Heard It Through The Grapevine}}\n[[Category:1967 singles]]\n[[Category:1968 singles]]\n[[Category:1976 singles]]\n[[Category:1981 singles]]\n[[Category:Marvin Gaye songs]]\n[[Category:Gladys Knight & the Pips songs]]\n[[Category:Creedence Clearwater Revival songs]]\n[[Category:The Miracles songs]]\n[[Category:Trini Lopez songs]]\n[[Category:Michael McDonald (musician) songs]]\n[[Category:Billboard Hot 100 number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Billboard Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs number-one singles]]\n[[Category:UK Singles Chart number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Grammy Hall of Fame Award recipients]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Barrett Strong]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Norman Whitfield]]\n[[Category:Motown singles]]\n[[Category:Tamla Records singles]]\n[[Category:Fantasy Records singles]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Norman Whitfield]]\n[[Category:1966 songs]]\n[[Category:Songs about infidelity]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Original song written and composed by Norman Whitfield and Barrett Strong}}\n{{About|the song|the album by Marvin Gaye|I Heard It Through the Grapevine (album)|the idiom|Wiktionary:hear through the grapevine}}\n{{redirect|Heard It Through the Grapevine|the South Korean television series|Heard It Through the Grapevine (TV series)}}\n\n{{Good article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2011}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = I Heard It Through the Grapevine\n| cover      = Marvin-Gaye-Grapevine.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Marvin Gaye]]\n| album      = [[I Heard It Through the Grapevine (album)|In the Groove]]\n| B-side     = You're What's Happening (in the World Today)\n| released   = October 30, 1968\n| format     = [[7-inch single]]\n| recorded   = February 3, 8, 13, 15, and April 10, 1967\n| studio     = [[Hitsville USA|Hitsville USA (Studio A)]], Detroit, Michigan\n| genre      = [[Soul music|Soul]], [[Rhythm and blues|R&B]]\n| length     = 3:16\n| label      = [[Motown|Tamla]]\n| writer     = {{hlist|[[Norman Whitfield]]|[[Barrett Strong]]}}\n| producer   = [[Norman Whitfield]]\n| prev_title = [[His Eye is on the Sparrow]]\n| prev_year  = 1968\n| next_title = [[Good Lovin' Ain't Easy to Come By]]\n| next_year  = 1969\n}}\n\"'''I Heard It Through the Grapevine'''\" is a song written by [[Norman Whitfield]] and [[Barrett Strong]] for [[Motown Records]] in 1966. The first recording of the song to be released was produced by Whitfield for [[Gladys Knight & the Pips]] and released as a single in September 1967; it went to number two in the ''Billboard'' chart.\n\n[[The Miracles]] first recorded the song on August 16, 1966<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://secondhandsongs.com/work/6417/originals#nav-entity|title=Original versions of I Heard It Through the Grapevine written by Norman Whitfield, Barrett Strong {{!}} SecondHandSongs|website=secondhandsongs.com|access-date=2019-10-23}}</ref> and included their version on their 1968 album, ''[[Special Occasion (The Miracles album)|Special Occasion]]''. The [[Marvin Gaye]] version was placed on his 1968 album ''[[I Heard It Through the Grapevine (album)|In the Groove]]'', where it gained the attention of radio disc jockeys, and Motown founder [[Berry Gordy]] finally agreed to its release as a single in October 1968, when it went to the top of the ''Billboard'' Pop Singles chart for seven weeks from December 1968 to January 1969 and became for a time the biggest hit single on the Motown label (Tamla).\n\nThe Gaye recording has since become an acclaimed soul classic, and in 2004, it was placed 81 on the ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' list of [[The 500 Greatest Songs of All Time]]. On the commemorative fortieth anniversary of the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 issue of [[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'' magazine]] in June 2008, Marvin Gaye's \"Grapevine\" was ranked sixty-fifth. It was also inducted to the [[Grammy Hall of Fame]] for \"historical, artistic and significant\" value.\n\nIn addition to being released several times by Motown artists, the song has been recorded by a range of musicians including [[Creedence Clearwater Revival]], who made an eleven-minute interpretation for their 1970 album, ''[[Cosmo's Factory]]''.\n\n==Composition==\nThe lyrics tell the story in the first person of the singer's feelings of betrayal and disbelief when he hears of his girlfriend's infidelity only indirectly \"through the 'grapevine'\".<ref>{{cite book|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=0bnU1c3xElQC&pg=PA328#v=onepage&q&f=false |title= The Popular Music Studies Reader |page= 328 |author= Andy Bennett |publisher= Routledge |date= December 14, 2005 |accessdate= September 17, 2012}}</ref>\n\nBy 1966, Barrett Strong, the singer on Motown Records' breakthrough hit, \"[[Money (That's What I Want)]]\", had the basics of a song he had started to write in Chicago, where the idea had come to him while walking down [[Michigan Avenue (Chicago)|Michigan Avenue]] that people were always saying \"I heard it through the grapevine\".<ref>{{cite book|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=8JRHnCMUVb8C&pg=PA77#v=onepage&q&f=false |title= Motown: The Golden Years|author= Bill Dahl |page= 77 |publisher= Krause Publications |date= February 28, 2011 |accessdate= September 15, 2012}}</ref> The phrase is associated with black slaves during the Civil War, who had their form of [[morse telegraph|telegraph]]: the human grapevine.<ref>{{cite book|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=SYrJZLjgDmIC&pg=PA147#v=onepage&q&f=false |title= America in So Many Words: Words That Have Shaped America |page= 147 |author= Allan Metcalf, David K. Barnhart |publisher= Houghton Mifflin Harcourt |year= 1999 |accessdate= September 18, 2012}}</ref><ref name=Shapiro/> Producer Norman Whitfield worked with Strong on the song, adding lyrics to Strong's basic Ray Charles influenced gospel tune and the single chorus line of \"I heard it through the grapevine\".<ref name=H-160>{{cite book|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=qXhwR_2Ka2UC&pg=PA160#v=onepage&q&f=false |title= Sonic Alchemy: Visionary Music Producers and Their Maverick Recordings |page= 160 |author= David N. Howard |publisher= Hal Leonard Corporation |date= June 11, 2004 |accessdate= September 16, 2012}}</ref> This was to be the first of a number of successful collaborations between Strong and Whitfield.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.songwritershalloffame.org/index.php/exhibits/bio/C338 |title= Songwriters Hall of Fame \u2013 Barrett Strong Biography |work= Songwritershalloffame.org |access-date= September 17, 2012 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20130121034444/http://www.songwritershalloffame.org/index.php/exhibits/bio/C338 |archive-date= January 21, 2013 |url-status= dead }}</ref>\n\n==Motown recordings==\nProducer Norman Whitfield recorded \"I Heard It Through the Grapevine\" with various Motown artists. The first known recording is with [[the Miracles]] on August 6, 1966, though there may also have been a recording with [[the Isley Brothers]], or at least Whitfield intended to record it with them; however, a track has not turned up \u2013 some Motown historians believe that a session may have been scheduled but cancelled.<ref name=H-160/><ref name=McLean>{{cite web|url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/northernireland/music/story_behind/grapevine.shtml |title= BBC Music: Stories Behind the Song: \"I Heard it Through the Grapevine\" |author= Ralph McLean |work= BBC.co.uk |date= April 2003 |accessdate= September 15, 2012}}</ref><ref>''Motown: The History'', page 56, Sharon Davis, Gullane, 1988</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Gladys Knight and the Pips \u2013 'I Heard It Through the Grapevine' |work=The Daily Record |author=Joel Francis |date=September 9, 2009 |url=http://joelfrancis.com/2009/09/09/gladys-knight-and-the-pips-%E2%80%93-%E2%80%9Ci-heard-it-through-the-grapevine%E2%80%9D/ |access-date=February 1, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090925012345/http://joelfrancis.com/2009/09/09/gladys-knight-and-the-pips-%E2%80%93-%E2%80%9Ci-heard-it-through-the-grapevine%E2%80%9D/ |archive-date=September 25, 2009 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The Miracles' version was not released as a single due to [[Berry Gordy]]'s veto during Motown's weekly quality control meetings; Gordy advised Whitfield and Strong to create a stronger single.<ref name=McLean/> The Miracles version later appeared on their 1968 ''[[Special Occasion (Miracles album)|Special Occasion]]'' album, and a slightly different take, possibly from the same session but unreleased, appeared on the 1998 compilation album, ''Motown Sings Motown Treasures''.<ref name=CS>{{cite book|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=eg0dpgvfVqEC&pg=PA92#v=onepage&q&f=false |title= Sounding Out Pop: Analytical Essays in Popular Music |page= 92 |author= John Covach, Mark Spicer |publisher= University of Michigan Press |date= June 22, 2010 |accessdate= September 16, 2012}}</ref>\n\nMarvin Gaye's version was recorded in spring 1967, and is the second known recording, though it was also rejected by Gordy as a single, and would also later go onto the album ''[[I Heard It Through the Grapevine (album)|In the Groove]]''. The third recording was in 1967 with Gladys Knight and the Pips in a new, faster arrangement. Gordy accepted the new arrangement and the Gladys Knight version was released as a single in September 1967, reaching number 2 in the charts. When Gaye's album with his version of Grapevine was released in August 1968, radio disc jockeys were playing the song, so Gordy had it released as a single in October, and it went to number one in December.<ref name=CS/>\n\nIn 1968, [[Bobby Taylor & the Vancouvers]] recorded a version for their debut album based on Gladys' recent hit; however, after hearing the Marvin Gaye version, they felt they'd made the wrong choice.<ref>{{cite book|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=8JRHnCMUVb8C&pg=PA318&lpg=PA318#v=onepage&q&f=falsee |title= Motown: The Golden Years |author= Bill Dahl |page= 318 |publisher= Krause Publications |date= February 28, 2011 |accessdate= September 15, 2012}}</ref> In 1969, Whitfield produced a version for [[the Temptations]] \"[[psychedelic soul]]\" album, ''[[Cloud Nine (The Temptations album)|Cloud Nine]]'', in which he \"brought compelling percussion to the fore, and relegated the piano well into the wings\".<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.allmusic.com/album/cloud-nine-mw0000192710 |title= Cloud Nine \u2013 The Temptations |author= Amy Hanson |work= allmusic.com |year= 2012 |accessdate= September 18, 2012}}</ref> In 1971, [[the Undisputed Truth]] recorded the song in a Marvin-styled version as did [[Bettye Lavette]] on her 1982 Motown album, ''Tell Me a Lie''.\n\n===Marvin Gaye===\n{{listen|filename=1968-marvin-gaye-grapevine.ogg|title=\"I Heard It Through the Grapevine\"|left|description=Marvin Gaye's version of the song |filetype=[[Ogg]]}}\n\nWhitfield recorded the song with [[Marvin Gaye]] over five sessions, the first on February 3, 1967, and the last on April 10, 1967.<ref name=Shapiro>{{cite book|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=GG1jtWGU0S8C&pg=PA122#v=onepage&q&f=false |title= Turn the Beat Around: The Secret History of Disco |pages= 122\u2013124 |author= Peter Shapiro |publisher= Macmillan |year= 2006 |accessdate= September 18, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://soulfuldetroit.com/archives/3190/2714.html?1048154254 |title= Marvin Gaye Session Dates  |work= Soulfuldetroit.com |year= 2010 |accessdate= September 18, 2012}}</ref> Recordings of this version took more than a month due to Whitfield overdubbing Gaye's vocals with that of [[the Andantes]]' background vocals, mixing in several tracks featuring [[the Funk Brothers]] on the rhythm track, and adding the string section from the [[Detroit Symphony Orchestra]] with an arrangement by [[Paul Riser]].<ref name=Shapiro/>\n\nThe session featuring Gaye led to an argument between the producer and singer. Whitfield wanted Gaye to perform the song in a higher [[Key (music)|key]] than his normal range,<ref name=H-160/> a move that had worked on [[David Ruffin]] during the recording of [[the Temptations]]' hit, \"[[Ain't Too Proud to Beg]]\". The mixture of Gaye's raspy vocals and the Andantes' sweeter harmonies made Whitfield confident that he had a hit; however, despite approval from Motown's Quality Control Department, Gordy blocked the release.<ref name=Posner>{{cite book|title= Motown: Music, Money, Sex, and Power|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GmyKDQAAQBAJ&pg=pa225#v=onepage&q&f=false |author= Gerald Posner |pages= 224\u2013225 |publisher= Random House |year=2002 |isbn=0-8129-7468-9|accessdate= August 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Gladys Knight & the Pips===\n{{listen|filename=1967-gladys-pips-grapevine.ogg|title=\"I Heard It Through the Grapevine\"|left|description=Gladys Knight and the Pips 1967 version of the song |filetype=[[Ogg]]}}\n\n[[Gladys Knight & the Pips]] recorded \"Grapevine\" on June 17, 1967, in Motown's Studio A, with Norman Whitfield as producer. After hearing [[Aretha Franklin]]'s version of \"[[Respect (song)|Respect]]\", Whitfield rearranged \"Grapevine\" to include some of the [[funk]] elements of the [[Muscle Shoals Rhythm Section]]. According to [[David Ritz]], Whitfield set to record a song that would \"out-funk\" Aretha. After Whitfield presented the demo tapes, [[Gladys Knight]], [[Merald \"Bubba\" Knight|Bubba Knight]], [[William Guest (singer)|William Guest]], and [[Edward Patten]] worked for several weeks on their vocal arrangement. To make the song suitable for Gladys, the first line of the second verse (''\"I know a man ain't supposed to cry/But these tears I can't hold inside\"'') was altered to (''\"Take a good look at these tears in my eyes/Baby, these tears I can't hold inside\"''). After much talk, Gordy reluctantly allowed the Pips' version to be a single on September 28, 1967, on Motown's Soul label.\n\n==Releases==\nThe Gladys Knight & the Pips version released on September 28, 1967, was on Motown's Soul label, with \"It\u2019s Time to Go Now\" on the [[A-side and B-side|B-side]]. Motown put little support behind it and the Pips relied on connections with DJs across the United States to get the record played. The Pips' version of \"Grapevine\" reached number one on the ''Billboard'' R&B chart on November 25, 1967, and stayed there for six weeks, making it the group's second R&B number one after 1961's \"Every Beat of My Heart\". It reached two on the ''Billboard'' Pop Singles chart<ref>{{cite book|title= Top R&B/Hip-Hop Singles: 1942\u20132004 |author= [[Joel Whitburn]] |year= 2004 |publisher= Record Research |page=330}}</ref> the same month, with [[the Monkees]]' \"[[Daydream Believer]]\" holding top spot. It was Motown's best-selling single to that point. The song was later placed on the Gladys Knight & the Pips album ''[[Everybody Needs Love (Gladys Knight & the Pips album)|Everybody Needs Love]]''.\n\nWhitfield wanted Gordy to release Gaye's \"Grapevine\" as a single, but Gordy did not want to release another version after the Pips had already made a hit out of it.<ref name=Posner/> In September 1968, Whitfield added \"Grapevine\" to Gaye's new album ''[[I Heard It Through the Grapevine (album)|In the Groove]]''.<ref name=Posner/> On release \"Grapevine\" became a radio hit and, according to Gordy himself, \"The DJs played it so much off the album that we had to release it as a single\".<ref>{{cite book|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=eg0dpgvfVqEC&pg=PA92#v=onepage&q&f=false |title= To Be Loved: The Music, the Magic, the Memories of Motown |author= [[Berry Gordy]] |page= 275 |publisher= [[Grand Central Pub.]] |date=  December 1, 1995 |accessdate= September 24, 2012}}</ref> So Gaye's version was released as a single on October 30, 1968. Gaye's \"I Heard It Through the Grapevine\" eventually outsold the Pips', and until [[The Jackson 5]]'s \"[[I'll Be There (Jackson 5 song)|I'll Be There]]\" 20 months later, was the biggest hit single of all time on the Motown label. It stayed at the top of the ''[[Billboard Hot 100|Billboard]]'' [[Billboard Hot 100|Pop Singles]] chart<ref name=\"unt\">{{cite web|url=https://digital.library.unt.edu/ark:/67531/metadc19831/m1/|title=Show 50 - The Soul Reformation: Phase three, soul music at the summit. &#91;Part 6&#93; :  UNT Digital Library|publisher=digital.library.unt.edu|accessdate=September 25, 2014}}</ref> for seven weeks, from December 14, 1968, to January 25, 1969. Gaye's \"Grapevine\" also held number one on the R&B chart during the same seven weeks,<ref>{{cite book|title= Top R&B/Hip-Hop Singles: 1942\u20132004 |author= [[Joel Whitburn]] |year= 2004 |publisher= Record Research |page= 225}}</ref> and stayed at number one in the United Kingdom for three weeks starting on March 26, 1969. The label was pleased with the success, although Gaye, depressed because of issues such as the illness of singing partner [[Tammi Terrell]] (which would kill her less than a year later), was quoted as saying that his success \"didn't seem real\" and that he \"didn't deserve it\".<ref name=Posner/>\n\nDue to the song's success, ''In the Groove'' was re-issued as ''I Heard It Through the Grapevine'' and peaked at number two on the R&B album chart and number sixty-three on the album chart, which was at the time Marvin's highest-charted solo studio effort to date. Because of the success of both versions, \"I Heard It Through the Grapevine\" was the first and last number one on the ''Billboard'' R&B chart in 1968: the Pips version was the first week of January, the Gaye version the last week of December. Gladys Knight was not pleased that Gaye's version usurped her own, and claimed that Gaye's version was recorded over an instrumental track Whitfield had prepared for a Pips song, an allegation Gaye denied.<ref>{{cite interview  |work= BBC Radio 2 |author= Marvin Gaye |interviewer= [[Paul Gambaccini]]|title=1976 interview with Marvin Gaye |year= 1976 |url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio2/soldonsong/songlibrary/ihearditthroughthegrapevine.shtml |accessdate= September 24, 2012}}</ref> In 1985, one year following Gaye's death, the song was re-released in the UK reaching number eight thanks to a [[Levi's]] commercial (starring [[Nick Kamen]]).<ref name=Robinson/>\n\n==Legacy==\nThe Gaye recording has become an acclaimed soul classic. In 2004, it was placed at number 80 on ''[[Rolling Stone]]'''s list of [[The 500 Greatest Songs of All Time]],<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/news/coverstory/500songs |title=The Rolling Stone 500 Greatest Songs of All Time |journal=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=December 9, 2004 |access-date=September 23, 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080622145429/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/coverstory/500songs |archive-date=June 22, 2008 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> with the comment that Whitfield had produced the song with a number of artists using different arrangements, and that on the Marvin Gaye recording he had a \"golden idea\" when he set the song \"in a slower, more mysterious tempo\".<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/6595925/i_heard_it_through_the_grapevine |title=The Rolling Stone 500 Greatest Songs of All Time |journal=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=December 9, 2004 |access-date=September 23, 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080621160207/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/6595925/i_heard_it_through_the_grapevine |archive-date=June 21, 2008 }}</ref>  In a new ''Rolling Stone'' list published in 2011, the single was placed slightly lower at number 81.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/the-500-greatest-songs-of-all-time-20110407/marvin-gaye-i-heard-it-through-the-grapevine-19691231 |title= 500 Greatest Songs Of All Time: Marvin Gaye, 'I Heard It Through the Grapevine' |work= RollingStone.com |accessdate= July 5, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn the commemorative fiftieth anniversary of the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 issue of [[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'' magazine]] in June 2008, the Marvin Gaye version was ranked as the sixty-fifth biggest song on the chart.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/specials/hot100/charts/top100-titles-70.shtml |title= Billboard's Greatest Songs of All Time |work= Billboard |accessdate= February 1, 2009}}</ref> It was also inducted to the [[Grammy Hall of Fame]] for \"historical, artistic and significant\" value.\n\n==Other versions==\n\nIn addition to being recorded several times by Motown artists, the song has been recorded by musicians including [[Creedence Clearwater Revival]] who recorded an 11-minute version for their 1970 album, ''[[Cosmo's Factory]]'',<ref>{{cite journal|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=R0UEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA40#v=onepage&q&f=false |title= Artists Are Color Blind When Looking At Copyrights |journal= [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |page= 40 |date= January 29, 1972 |accessdate= September 24, 2012}}</ref> that was released as a single, reaching 43 on ''Billboard''<nowiki/>'s chart, with more modest success in other countries,<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.allmusic.com/artist/creedence-clearwater-revival-mn0000131627/awards |title= Creedence Clearwater Revival awards on Allmusic |work= Allmusic |publisher= Rovi Corporation |accessdate= July 17, 2013}}</ref> and [[funk]] musician [[Roger Troutman]] whose extended version (nearly 11 minutes itself) lifted off his 1981 solo album, ''[[The Many Facets of Roger]]'',<ref>{{cite book|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=DykffzkFALoC&pg=PA659#v=onepage&q&f=false |title= Knocking on Heaven's Door: Rock Obituaries |page= 659 |author= Nick Talevski |publisher= Omnibus Press |date= August 1, 2006 |accessdate= September 23, 2012}}</ref> brought the song back to number one on the R&B chart in early November of 1981, marking the third time the single reached the top spot on that chart. It also made the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], but was not a Pop success this time around, peaking at number 79.<ref>{{cite book|title= Top R&B/Hip-Hop Singles: 1942\u20132004 |author= [[Joel Whitburn]] |year= 2004 |publisher= Record Research |page= 499}}</ref> British punk band [[The Slits]] recorded the song in a post-punk style as a bonus track on their 1979 album [[Cut (The Slits album)|Cut]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/7803-cut/|title=The Slits: Cut|website=Pitchfork|language=en|access-date=2019-04-29}}</ref> [[Queen Latifah]] used the music as a basis for her 1998 single \"[[Paper (Queen Latifah song)|Paper]]\", produced by [[Pras Michel]] for her album ''[[Order in the Court]]''.<ref>{{cite journal |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=4nXHlKc5kCwC&pg=PA22#v=onepage&q&f=false |journal=Ebony|page=22|title=Sounding Off \u2013 Review of Order in the Court |author=Lynn Norment|date=September 1988|accessdate=September 16, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n\"I Heard It Through the Grapevine\" has been used twice in television commercials \u2013 each time using session musicians recreating the style of the Marvin Gaye version. For the 1985 [[Levi's]] 501 commercial \"Launderette\", featuring male model [[Nick Kamen]], agency [[Bartle Bogle Hegarty|BBH]] and director Roger Lyons, owing to budgetary constraints, brought in [[Karl Jenkins]] and [[Mike Ratledge]] to recreate the sound of the Marvin Gaye original with Tony Jackson, a [[Barbadian people|Barbadian]] background singer for [[Paul Young]], handling vocals and [[P. P. Arnold]] on backing vocals.<ref name=Robinson/><ref>{{cite journal|author= Emma Hall |title= Campaign Screen: Music and Sound Design - Production. Top of the Pops |journal= [[Campaign (magazine)|Campaign]] |date=  November 22, 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author= Sam Ingleby |title= Karl Jenkins: Fanfare for the Common Man |journal= [[The Independent]] |date= May 17, 2004}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.ronroker.com/Latestreleases.htm |title= Ron Roker - Latest Releases |author= Ron Roker |year= 2009 |accessdate= July 17, 2013 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20131127073157/http://ronroker.com/Latestreleases.htm |archive-date= November 27, 2013 |url-status= dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=XDUOAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA73#v=onepage&q&f=false |title= Fashion Marketing |author= Janet Bohdanowicz, Liz Clamp |page= 73 |publisher= Routledge |year= 1994 |accessdate= September 16, 2012}}</ref> The commercial's success prompted [[Motown Records|Tamla-Motown]] to re-release Gaye's single with the Levi's 501 logo on the sleeve \u2014 \"an example of integrated marketing almost before the term was invented\".<ref>{{cite journal|author= Caroline Marshall |title= Campaign Hall of Fame |journal= Campaign |date= December 20, 1999}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.musikzimmer.ch/pics/covers/singles/82.jpg |title= Marvin Gaye - I Heard It Through the Grapevine |accessdate= July 17, 2013}}</ref> The record went to number eight on the UK Singles chart, marking its second chart performance.<ref name=Robinson>{{cite book|url= http://www.aber.ac.uk/media/Modules/MC30820/launderette.html |title= The Sunday Times 100 Greatest TV Ads |pages= 119\u2013121 |author= Mark Robinson |publisher= HarperCollins |date= March 1, 2001 |accessdate= September 16, 2012}}</ref> A year later, in 1986, [[Buddy Miles]] was the singer for the [[clay animation]] group [[The California Raisins]] which sang it as part a TV advertising campaign.<ref>{{cite journal|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=VxMEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA60#v=onepage&q&f=false |title= Buddy Miles, 60 |journal= Billboard |page= 60 |author= Kristina Tunzi |date= March 15, 2008 |accessdate= September 17, 2012}}</ref>\n\nMarvin Gaye's version of the song is used in the opening credits of ''[[The Big Chill (film)|The Big Chill]]'' (1983) as each of the main characters gets to hear (through the \"grapevine\") about the death of their college friend, and then travels to his funeral; the song serves in an [[extradiegetic]] fashion to both unite the main characters' friendship and to locate it nostalgically for the viewer.<ref>{{cite book|url= https://archive.org/details/popularmusicfilm00iani |url-access= registration |title= Popular Music and Film |page= [https://archive.org/details/popularmusicfilm00iani/page/168 168] |author= Ian Inglis |publisher= Wallflower Press |year= 2003 |accessdate= September 17, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=37maxOYnf_kC&pg=PA44#v=onepage&q&f=false |title= The Multi-Protagonist Film |page= 168 |author= Mar\u00eda del Mar Azcona |publisher= John Wiley & Sons |date= July 11, 2011 |accessdate= September 17, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=vbzPd4uegeUC&pg=PA115#v=onepage&q&f=false |title= The Sound of Pictures |page= 115 |author= Andrew Ford |publisher= Schwartz Publishing |year= 2011 |accessdate= September 18, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Personnel==\n===Marvin Gaye version===\n* Lead vocals by [[Marvin Gaye]]\n* Background vocals by [[The Andantes]]: Jackie Hicks, Marlene Barrow and Louvain Demps\n* [[Hammond organ]] by [[Earl Van Dyke]]<ref name=Shapiro/>\n* [[Wurlitzer electric piano]] by [[Johnny Griffith (musician)|Johnny Griffith]]\n* Drums by [[Richard \"Pistol\" Allen]]<ref name=Shapiro/> and [[Uriel Jones]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/culture-obituaries/music-obituaries/5062764/Uriel-Jones.html|title=Uriel Jones  Obituary|date=29 March 2009|work=telegraph.co.uk}}</ref>\n* Bass guitar by [[James Jamerson]]\n* Percussion by [[Jack Ashford]]\n* Guitar by [[Joe Messina]]\n* Instrumentation by [[the Funk Brothers]] and the [[Detroit Symphony Orchestra]]\n* String arrangement by [[Paul Riser]]<ref name=Shapiro/>\n\n===Gladys Knight & The Pips===\n* Lead vocals by [[Gladys Knight]]\n* Backing vocals by [[Merald \"Bubba\" Knight|Merald Knight]], [[William Guest (singer)|William Guest]], and [[Edward Patten]]\n* Instrumentation by the [[Funk Brothers]]\n** Drums by [[Benny Benjamin]]\n\n==Charts and certifications==\n===Weekly charts===\n;Gladys Knight & the Pips\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1967-68)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n|Canada ''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'' Top Singles<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.100145&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.100145.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.100145|title=Item Display - RPM - Library and Archives Canada |website=Collectionscanada.gc.ca |date=1967-12-23 |accessdate=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|-\n|[[UK Singles Chart|UK]] \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|47\n|-\n|US ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]]<ref>''Joel Whitburn's Top Pop Singles 1955\u20131990'' - {{ISBN|0-89820-089-X}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|-\n|US [[Cash Box (magazine)|''Cash Box'']] Top 100<ref>[http://cashboxmagazine.com/archives/60s_files/19680113.html Cash Box Top 100 Singles, January 13, 1968]</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|-\n|}\n;Marvin Gaye\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Chart (1968\u201369)\n!Peak<br/>position\n|-\n|Australia ([[Go-Set|Go-Set Top 40]])<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.poparchives.com.au/gosetcharts/1969/19690402.html 